ğŸ‘‰ Pandas Data Cleaning means fixing messy data using Pandas functions so the data becomes correct and usable.

Real-world data is usually messy â€” it may have:
-Missing values
-Duplicate rows
-Wrong data types
-Outliers
-Formatting issues

Data cleaning fixes these problems before analysis or ML. Cleaning includes handling missing values, correcting errors, standardizing formats, and removing duplicates.

ğŸ§  Main Pandas Data Cleaning Tasks (Simple)
1ï¸âƒ£ Handling Missing Values (Very Important)
Missing values are very common in real datasets.
ğŸ‘‰ Pandas methods:
dropna() â†’ remove missing rows/columns
fillna() â†’ fill missing values.

Example:
df.dropna()
df.fillna(0)
You can also fill using mean values:
   df.fillna(df.mean())
Dropping removes incomplete records, while filling keeps data but replaces missing values.

2ï¸âƒ£ Removing Duplicate Data
Duplicates can give wrong counts and wrong analysis.
ğŸ‘‰ Pandas methods:
duplicated() â†’ check duplicates
drop_duplicates() â†’ remove duplicates
Example:
df.drop_duplicates()
You can remove duplicates based on specific columns also.

3ï¸âƒ£ Fixing Data Types
Sometimes numbers come as text or dates as string.
ğŸ‘‰ Method:
df["age"] = df["age"].astype(int)
Correct data types are important for calculations and ML models.

4ï¸âƒ£ Standardizing Text / Category Data
Example problems:
"HYD" vs "hyd" vs " Hyderabad "
"Male" vs "male"
ğŸ‘‰ Example:
df["city"] = df["city"].str.lower().str.strip()
Standardizing makes grouping and analysis accurate.

5ï¸âƒ£ Handling Outliers
Outliers = Very abnormal values.
Example:
Salary = 1 crore when others = 50k
Methods:
Remove outliers
Replace with mean / median
Cap values
Example:
df["age"] = np.clip(df["age"], lower, upper)
Handling outliers improves model accuracy.

